attributes.title: Sherman et al. Replication Materials
attributes.description: Materials for Sherman et al., 2012 replication effort.

data.value: No, no data have been collected for this study yet.

name.value: Pre-registered Direct Replication: Reinvestigating the Disgust-Perception Link

other.value:
Secondary analyses

On trait purity: 

Secondary H1a: We predict that trait purity, like trait disgust, will influence ratings of incidental disgust (e.g., how disgusting the images seem) such that individuals high in trait purity will report higher ratings of incidental disgust 

Secondary H1b: We will also test the critical three-way interaction between induced emotion, end of spectrum, and trait purity. This is the critical analysis from Sherman, Haidt, and Clore (2002) but replacing trait disgust with trait purity. We predict that individuals high in trait purity in the induced disgust condition (compared to the fear and control conditions) will evidence enhanced detection at the light end of the spectrum relative to dark end performance.

On incidental disgust:

The original authors did not find a two-way interaction between incidental disgust and end of spectrum on detection. We will investigate this because we updated the induction images, but it is not critical to the interpretation of this replication and is not critical to the key finding in the original paper.


Piloting of detection stimuli:

Twenty participants will be recruited prior to the main experiment to ensure that the detection stimuli are still well calibrated (performance hovers around 70%, as in the original experiment). If performance is well above 70%, then this will trigger a separate calibration study where new detection stimuli are created with decreased contrast (e.g., making it more difficult to detect the number). If performance is well below 70%, this will also trigger a calibration study but with detection stimuli with increased contrast (e.g., making it slightly easier to detect the number). 

Planned protocol that follows in the event of a replication failure:

If the replication outlined in Experiment 1 fails, updated NAPS images (compared to IAPS used in Sherman et al., 2012) may be a barrier to interpreting the null finding. As such, in the case of a SUCCESSFUL manipulation check, no additional version of the study will be conducted. Instead, we will utilize Bayesian analyses (using the brms package in R) to explore support for the null hypothesis. In the case of an UNSUCCESSFUL manipulation check, this will trigger an exact replication of Experiment 1 (using the original IAPS images).

sample.value: A power analyses using PANGEA (Westfall, 2015) was conducted. To achieve around 85% power, with an effect size of d=.3, 120 participants are necessary to replicate the critical 3-way interaction (trait disgust by state disgust by end of spectrum) with this design. We added 10 participants to the total sample (N=130) to ensure that we meet the standard of 2.5x the original sample, which was 44 (Brandt, et al 2014), even in the case that any participants are excluded (based on the above listed criteria).

analyses.value:
Manipulation checks
We will test whether the emotion induction was successful after each block; we expect that the disgusting images will induce more disgust than fear whereas the fear-inducing images will induce more fear than disgust. To test this, we will adopt the standard used in Sherman and colleagues (2012) –if induced disgust is rated significantly more disgusting than fearful and if induced fear is rated significantly more fearful than disgusting, this will constitute a successful manipulation. A successful manipulation check will determine whether or not a follow-up study is conducted utilizing the IAPS images from the Sherman et al. 2012 paper (discussed in more detail in the "Other" section below). 

Task ceiling/floor effects
A pilot experiment will be conducted by recruiting 20 participants. Average performance at either end of the spectrum that is above 90% or below 20% correct will constitute ceiling and floor effects, respectively. If this occurs, the lack of variability in the dependent variable will constitute a shift to a calibration study where new detection stimuli will be tested until performance hover at around 70%. 

Primary Analyses
We will examine the influence of emotion induction and trait disgust sensitivity on perceptual contrast sensitivity. Following the statistical analyses conducted in Sherman and colleagues (2012), we will conduct mixed-effects models with two levels (using the glmer function in R). The within-subjects factors: end of spectrum (light versus dark) and dummy-coded within-subjects induction (disgust, disgust control, fear, fear control) will be entered as a Level 1 predictor and modeled as random. The between-subjects trait factors (z-scored trait disgust and z-scored trait fear/anxiety) will be entered as a Level 2 predictor.

dependent.value: The main dependent variable of interest is accuracy (contrast detection performance), which is assessed in a binary manner (1= correct number identified, 0 = incorrect number identified).

conditions.value: The experiment will consist of four within-subjects experimental blocks (crossed-factors): disgust, disgust control, fear, fear control, to be counterbalanced to assess potential order effects. Fear and disgust are made up of NAPS images and their corresponding control are made from scrambled pixels from the respective induction stimuli.

hypothesis.value:
The predictions are ordered in importance to the critical predictions in the original study. 

Three Critical Hypotheses: 

H1: There is no predicted marginal effect of end of spectrum (as in Study 3 of Sherman, Haidt, & Clore, 2012). 

H2: It is predicted that trait disgust sensitivity enhances detection of deviations from whiteness (compared to deviations from darkness). 

H3: We predict a three-way interaction between end of spectrum, trait disgust, and emotion induction, such that individuals high in trait disgust in the induced disgust condition (compared to the induced fear and control conditions) will show enhanced detection at the light end of the spectrum relative to dark end performance. (This is the targeted effect to replicate from Sherman et al., 2012).

Additional Hypotheses: 

On fear:

H4: We predict that there will be a marginal effect of trait fear on performance. This is in contrast to the original Sherman, Haidt, and Clore (2012) paper where they did not find this effect. We predict that trait fear/anxiety will enhance detection across both ends of the spectrum because we have improved the measure of trait fear.

H5: We predict that incidental fear will enhance performance across both the light and dark ends of the light to dark spectrum. 

On ratings of disgust:

H6: We predict that trait disgust will increase ratings of incidental disgust (i.e., how disgusting the images seem, as found in Sherman et al., 2012) such that individuals high in trait disgust will report increased feelings of disgust after they view the induction images.

study_type_other.value:
Data collection will be terminated either (1) when the desired sample size is met or (2) if we get to 130 with a short amount of time remaining in a given semester, we will collect data up to the end of the semester. 

This pre-registration is part of a registered replication under review at Psychological Science. For detailed information, the full manuscript is posted under the same project heading here on OSF.

attributes.title: Mike McDermott Final Project
attributes.description: this current study wanted to examine was that if there was an interaction with these two topics (how strict one’s parents were about alcohol and gender differences), and not only look at just one of them. This is important because as stated, alcoholism makes no exceptions in claiming its victims. This is a serious problem worldwide and with more knowledge about it we can better combat this illness and help prevent it from occurring in others as well.

q1.value: Michael McDermott, Amanda Monetti, Madison Pristera, Caitlyn Pritchard, Raymond Zuhowski, Samantha Zupko, Clare Conry-Murray, Thomas Joseph Harrison, Mackenzie Gillen, Minka Bolognese, Ella Campbell, Patricia Carballo, Sheahan Collins, Christen Dockins, Madeline Eickman, Maura Flynn, Robert Gentilucci, Ryenn Hayes, Amanda Herzig, Tess Hodder, Gabriel Legido, Ann McConnon, Alyssa McDougall, Kara McSweeney, Corinne O'Neill, Claire Pier, Allison Quinter, Carley Rose, Lauren Rossi, Ashley Santos, Gabriella Senni, Brendan Steigerwald, Nolan Vagnozzi, Alexa Weber

q2.value: the current study because the current study will hypothesize that people who had less strict parents will be more likely to engage in risk taking behavior when consuming alcohol. The study will also hypothesize that men are more likely to engage in risk taking behavior when consuming alcohol than women.

q3.value: Observational Study - Data is collected from study subjects that are not randomly assigned to a treatment. This includes surveys, “natural experiments,” and regression discontinuity designs.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value: This study will have a within-subjects design and will be a 2 x 2 factorial design.

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: The planned sample for this study will be young adults, preferably in the 18 – 29 year old age range. If this person does not drink alcohol, their results will be excluded. The survey will be distributed with a link via text messaging, social media, and email. There will be about a one week data collection period. Participation in this survey will be free.

q11.value: The ideal sample size for this study will be 20.

question.value: The variables that will be measured are: gender, how strict one's parents were about drinking alcohol, and how likely one is to engage in risk taking behavior when consuming alcohol.
This study will be using a one way ANOVA to interpret the raw data.

attributes.title: The primitives of the indexical space
attributes.description:
This is a follow up on a previous experiment pre-registered here: https://osf.io/r684g. 

The main goal of this project is to test whether context-dependent expressions of different classes (locatives and personal pronouns) share a common semantic basis: Can we analyse both personal and spatial indexicals in terms of an analogous set of features? 

In the previous experiment (henceforth, Experiment 1), we tested whether, when learners are trained on one partition for pronouns, they generalize it to locatives. The preliminary results of Experiment 1 suggest that this is indeed the case: After being trained on a participant partition of the person space, learners are more likely to infer the same partition for the locative space.
 
In Experiment 2 we aim at testing whether this bias is bidirectional: Do learners also generalize a learned locative partition to a person partition?

q2.value: We test the hypotheses, based on Harbour (2016), that spatial indexicals use the same set of features as person systems. From this hypothesis, we derive a further learning-based hypothesis: learners assume (unless they get evidence to the contrary), a single underlying partition for both kinds of indexicals. We will assess this hypothesis by testing whether, when learners are trained on one partition for locatives, they generalize it to personal pronouns.

q3.value: Experiment - A researcher randomly assigns treatments to study subjects, this includes field or lab experiments. This is also known as an intervention experiment and includes randomized controlled trials.

value: No blinding is involved in this study.

question.value:
We have a between-subjects design with a single factor, Condition, with two levels. 
Each Condition (level) determines which combination of person and spatial indexicals participants are trained on. Participants in all conditions are first taught a complete locative system (Phase 1), then exposed to part of a pronominal system (Phase 2A) and finally tested on how they extrapolate the pronominal forms they have learned to a remaining person meaning (Phase 2B). Conditions differ on the characteristics of each of these phases. 

Condition 1. Author bipartition (2+3) for locatives, Author or Participant bipartition for locatives?
Phase 1: Exposure to author bipartition,  where there is one locative form for spaces in the vicinity of the speaker (e.g., 'hiti') and another locative form  (e.g., 'hodo') for spaces not in the vicinity of the speaker. 
Phase 2A: Training on one pronominal form for the first person singular and another pronominal form for the third person singular.    
Phase 2B: Testing which pronominal form (of the ones they learned in Phase 2A) would participants use to refer to the addressee?

Condition 2. Participant bipartition (1+2) for person, Author or Participant bipartition for locatives?
Phase 1: Exposure to participant bipartition,  where there is one locative form for spaces in the vicinity of the speaker or the addressee (e.g., 'hiti') and another locative form  (e.g., 'hodo') for spaces not in the vicinity of the speaker or addressee. 
Phase 2A: Training on one pronominal form for the first person singular and another pronominal form for the third person singular.    
Phase 2B: Testing which pronominal form (of the ones they learned in Phase 2A) would participants use to refer to the addressee?

Participants are required to learn the full locative system, and only those who perform accurately during testing (>66% accuracy rate) are allowed to continue with the experiment.

q7.value: Participants are randomly assigned to one of the two Conditions described above. The experiment has two basic phases, each divided in training and testing blocks. Items within each block are presented in a random order.

q8.value: Registration prior to creation of data

question.value: Participants will be recruited through Amazon Mechanical Turk and will be paid 10 USD/h. Participants will be excluded if they are not self-reported native English speakers. See below for addition exclusion-criteria based on performance and attention checks.

q11.value: We aim for a total of between 50 and 60 participants per condition (about 200 participants in total) **after all exclusions** (see below)

q12.value: Sample size based on previous studies using similar paradigms in an online format.  Our size requirement is on the sample used for the analyses, after exclusion based on participants' performance on an attentional check at the beginning of the experiment and on the first phase of the experiment.

question.value: Our study will manipulate one between-subject variable Condition (2 levels).

In Phase 1, participants are taught two locative forms. These locatives are used to express 3 possible locations as a function of their proximity to different speech participants: spaces close to the speaker, spaces close to the addressee and other spaces (close to other people who are not participants in the conversation). 
Two of these locative meanings share a single form (i.e. they are are homophonous; depending on the Condition, as specified previously). Participants are tested on how well they have learned the mapping between forms and meanings. The dependent variable for the first phase of the experiment will then be accuracy rates: a binary response variable indicating whether the form chosen for a given meaning is CORRECT or INCORRECT, according to the language they were trained on.  

In Phase 2, participants are first taught two distinct pronominal forms, one used to convey the first person meaning and another one the third person meaning. 
Then, they are asked to choose which one of these two forms they would use to convey the second person meaning. 
We will analyse which one of the two taught forms participants use to convey each person category (first, second and third). 
For trained forms (first and third person meanings), this will give us accuracy scores indicating whether the form chosen for a given meaning is CORRECT or INCORRECT.
Responses for the held-out category (second person) will either collapse the second person with the first person, which would be compatible with an participant partition of the person space,  or with the third, which would be compatible with an author partition. 
We will quantify whether responses match or not the participant bipartition.

We will use logistic mixed-effects regression models to analyse the results.
We aim to test whether participants generalize the partition they learned for locatives to personal pronouns. 

Recall that the two experimental conditions only differ on the locative training: In Condition 1, participants are trained on an author bipartition for locatives; and in Condition 2 participants are trained on a participant bipartition. If the locative system participants are trained on influences their behaviour wrt locatives, we expect the rate of responses consistent with a participant bipartition to be higher in Condition 2 than in Condition 1. 

We will then run a model testing the effect of Condition on the response for the held-out category. This response variable is categorical: coded as 1 or 0 depending on whether it matches or not the participant bipartition on trials involving the held-out (untrained) pronominal meaning.  We will also include random by-participant intercepts. We will use a treatment contrast coding scheme with Condition 2 as the baseline.

q18.value:
We will encode the responses for the held-out category as follows:

If held-out form (vicinity of addressee) == vicinity of speaker, 1; otherwise, 0.

q19.value:
We will use the standard alpha level of 0.05 to determine significance.  We will follow the standard practice for generalised linear models and obtain p-values based on asymptotic Wald tests. 

The p-value for the model intercept will tell us whether or not the log odds of  selecting one form over other is significantly different from 0, i.e., that the percentage chance in which participants select the held-out form 1 is significantly different from 50%. 

The coefficient indicates in which direction: given the coding scheme above, positive values would indicate more extrapolation towards a participant-partition, and negative towards an author partition. 

If participants in the baseline Condition (Condition 2) are consistently extrapolating towards a participant partition, we would expect a positive coefficient. 

The p-value for the fixed effect of Condition will reveal whether there is a responses in the two conditions are significantly different from each other. We expect the effect of Condition to be significant.

q20.value:
Participants who have accuracy rates below 66% in Phase 1 won't be allowed to continue with Phase 2. 

We will exclude from the analysis participants who fail to perform accurately in at least 66% of trials of each training category during the test phase. This corresponds to 8 correct responses out of 12 per training category.

q21.value: We don't predict to have any missing data (forced choice task)

q22.value:
Early piloting suggests there might be a bias for inferring the participant partition regardless of training Condition. If this is the case, we will run a follow-up to assess to determine whether this preference is independent of the locative training at all. In other words, we will run a baseline condition to test what is the extrapolation pattern for pronouns in absence of any locative training.  

NB: In previous work, we have shown that learners indeed tend to generalize to participant bipartitions (1st vs. 2nd=3rd) in this kind of extrapolation experiments. However, this study involve homophony of plural (rather than singular) forms.

q23.value: The experiment included an attentional check at the beginning of the experiment to prevent participants from doing the experiment without reading the instructions. Participants who failed to pass this attentional check were not paid nor taken into account for the analyses.

The dependent variable for the first phase of the experiment will then be accuracy rates: a binary response variable indicating whether the form chosen for a given meaning is CORRECT or INCORRECT, according to the language they were trained on.  

In Phase 2, participants are first taught two distinct pronominal forms, one used to convey the first person meaning and another one the third person meaning. 
Then, they are asked to choose which one of these two forms they would use to convey the second person meaning. 
We will analyse which one of the two taught forms participants use to convey each person category (first, second and third). 
For trained forms (first and third person meanings), this will give us accuracy scores indicating whether the form chosen for a given meaning is CORRECT or INCORRECT.
Responses for the held-out category (second person) will either collapse the second person with the first person, which would be compatible with an participant partition of the person space,  or with the third, which would be compatible with an author partition. 
We will quantify whether responses match or not the participant bipartition.

We will use logistic mixed-effects regression models to analyse the results.
We aim to test whether participants generalize the partition they learned for locatives to personal pronouns. 

Recall that the two experimental conditions only differ on the locative training: In Condition 1, participants are trained on an author bipartition for locatives; and in Condition 2 participants are trained on a participant bipartition. If the locative system participants are trained on influences their behaviour wrt locatives, we expect the rate of responses consistent with a participant bipartition to be higher in Condition 2 than in Condition 1. 

We will then run a model testing the effect of Condition on the response for the held-out category. This response variable is categorical: coded as 1 or 0 depending on whether it matches or not the participant bipartition on trials involving the held-out (untrained) pronominal meaning.  We will also include random by-participant intercepts. We will use a treatment contrast coding scheme with Condition 2 as the baseline.
